post_text:
Our award-winning Family Resource Center is always accepting donations from our wonderful Salinas Community and beyond. Our Family Resource Center (FRC) helps our homeless population, foster kids, and our most neediest families. Last school year, our FRC helped over 150,000 individuals and has distributed, in collaboration with the Monterey County Food Bank and National Guard, over 870,000 pounds of food to our community since the beginning of school closures.

If you would like to donate and help your local community, here are some of our most urgent needs:
- Small hand sanitizers
- Socks for children, boys and girls, size medium and large only
- Disposable masks
- Disinfectant table wipes
- Combs and brushes
- Deodorant small size
- Small Kleenex
- Canned food
- Rice, beans, pasta
- Non-perishable snacks
- Diapers, Size 6 and pull-ups
- Toilet paper

You can call our Family Resource Center Homeless Liason, Cheryl Camany if you have any questions or need any clarification at (831) 809-3636 or you can email her at ccamany@salinascity.k12.ca.us.

#SCESDShines

Friendly Reminder:
Due to current air quality conditions caused by our local fires, we have temporarily revised our food distrubtion schedule.

We will serve meals on Mondays, only.
Enrolled SCESD students will receive 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches for the week. Distribution times will be at 7:30-8:30am and 10:00am-1:00pm.

In addition to our school-sites locations, for students who regularly ride the bus, we will provide meals from 1:30 pm to 2:15 pm at these specific bus stop locations:

- Hebbron Heights
- Laurel Heights
- Lunsford St
- Calle Cebu Street

Students do not need to be present when picking up meals. You will just need to provide your child‚Äôs name and school to the meal clerk.

When attending our food distributions, please wear a mask and follow all social/physical distancing protocols.

See you then! #SCESDShinesF

post_text:
In an effort to stay within compliance, Salinas City Elementary School District is holding stakeholder input sessions around our Learning Continuity and Attendance Plan.

Our virtual meetings will take place on Wednesday, August 26, 2020. English Session will be from 5:00 - 6:00 pm. Spanish Session will be from 6:30 - 7:30 pm.

The areas we will be asking feedback on are:
- Continuity of Learning: Increased or improved services for foster youth, English Learners, and low-income, including students experiencing homelessness
- Addressing pupil learning loss
- Mental health and social-emotional well-being
- Pupil engagement and outreach
- School nutrition

Below are the Meeting IDs for both sessions:

English Session
5:00 - 6:00 pm
Meeting ID: 933 4876 7116
Password: 724041
Quick Link: https://zoom.us/j/93348767116?pwd=R0RERWlHRUQ1czRuYk01WW1VNDlOUT09

Spanish Session
6:30 - 7:30 pm
Meeting ID: 978 1317 1516
Password: 651998
Quick Link: https://zoom.us/j/97813171516?pwd=UDNGb1JqWjVKK2ZzUzFsZk9ydE9Zdz09

We hope you're able to attend.
#SCESDShines

post_text:
Monday, August 10, marks the first day of school for Salinas City Elementary School District. We will be providing meals at all 14 school site locations, twice a day, Monday through Thursday.

On Thursdays, students will receive an additional meal for Friday.

Food distribution will be from 10:00 am - 1:00 pm and 3:00 pm - 4:00 pm for all Salinas City Elementary School District students only.

Note: Students, enrolled in SCESD, will be allowed to receive one meal per day. Students do not need to be present when picking up meals.

When attending our food distribution, please wear your mask and follow social distancing protocols.

For more information about our food distribution, visit our website at www.salinascityesd.org.

post_text:
As the start of the 2020-21 school year slowly approaches, many of our families are unsure of what the next school year will look like. We hope to provide some information and clarity around our Reopening Plan.

We will be having a VIRTUAL Community Town Hall Meeting about the Reopening of Schools on July 8, 2020. 10:00 am for Spanish and 6:00 pm for English.

During the virtual meeting, we will explain our two instructional models available for 2020-2021, share guidelines for the next school year, and allow for a question/answer period for families.

Additional details to come by Tuesday, July 7th.

It will be accessible by the public and live-streamed on our website (www.salinascityesd.org) and YouTube page (bit.ly/scesdyoutube).

If you would like to submit a question, please follow the link.
https://bit.ly/3dUff7z
Submit your questions by Tuesday, July 7, 2020, by 4:00 pm

Salinas City Elementary School District has transitioned its Food Distribution into our Seamless Summer Feeding Program.

We are serving meals, Monday through Thursday, at three locations from 11:30 am - 1:00 pm.

Our three locations are:
Boronda Meadows Elementary (915 Larkin Drive)
Los Padres Elementary (1130 John Street)
El Gabilan Elementary (1256 Linwood Drive)

On Thursdays, an additional meal will be included to have for Friday.

Feel free to stop by and take advantage of our Summer Feeding Program. #SCESDShines

post_text:
The following is important information regarding our newly revised Food Distribution Schedule.

Starting today, April 20th, until further notice, SCESD will serve meals Monday through Wednesday from 11:30am - 1:00pm.

On Monday and Wednesdays, we will continue to distribute meals from our (9) regular site locations. On Tuesdays, we will ONLY serve meals at Kammann, Mission Park and Sherwood Elementary schools.

Students will receive a free bagged lunch and breakfast for the following day to any children, ages 1 - 18, in any easy drive-thru or walk up location. On Wednesdays, students will receive an additional (4) meals for Thursday and Friday.

We highly recommend using the drive-thru and, if possible, use a face mask. If you walk up, please practice social and physical distancing protocols.

For more information about our Food Distribution schedule, please visit our website at salinascityesd.org.

Monterey County Office of Education and 24 County School Districts release new information regarding the extension of school closures.

Today the State Superintendent of Public Instruction Tony Thurmond released information that stated, ‚ÄúDue to the current safety concerns and needs for ongoing social distancing it currently appears that our students will not be able to return to school campuses before the end of the school year. This is in no way to suggest that school is over for the year, but rather we should put all efforts into strengthening our delivery of education through distance learning.‚Äù

Please read carefully.

post_text:
Monterey Bay CUE is holding its 3rd Annual Student Powered Film Festival and is opening submissions on January 22nd and due on March 6th!

This film festival is to provide students with a creative outlet in which they can express themselves and give themselves a voice. It also serves to educate teachers on ways to authentically implement technology in the classroom.

Submission are open for students in Kindergarten through High School living in Monterey, Santa Cruz and San Benito counties.

Each year, the goal of the festival is to promote and reinforce conservation. This year's theme is Earth Day.

If you have any questions, please contact Krysta Bradley by emailing her at kbradley@salinascity.k12.ca.us. For more information, please visit http://www.mbcue.com/film-festival.html.

Best of luck!! #MBCUE #SCESDShines
